# Why Do People Think COVID-19 Is a Hoax? An In-Depth Analysis

The COVID-19 pandemic has not only been a global health crisis but also a fertile ground for misinformation, conspiracy theories, and skepticism about the virus's existence and severity. A significant portion of the population in various countries has expressed disbelief in the reality of COVID-19, with some even labeling it a hoax. This report explores the multifaceted reasons behind why people think COVID-19 is a hoax, drawing on psychological, social, political, and informational factors supported by empirical data and scholarly research.

---

## Prevalence of COVID-19 Hoax Beliefs

Surveys conducted in different countries reveal that a notable minority of people believe COVID-19 is a hoax or exaggerated. For example, a University of Oxford study surveying 2,500 adults in England in May 2020 found that more than 21% of respondents believed the virus was a hoax to some extent, while 62% believed it was man-made to some degree ([Young, 2020](https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-hoax-government-misleading-man-made-survey-a9527876.html)). Similarly, a YouGov poll in the United States in March 2020 found that 13% of Americans believed the COVID-19 crisis was a hoax ([Robson, 2020](https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20200406-why-smart-people-believe-coronavirus-myths)).

---

## Psychological Foundations of Hoax Beliefs

### 1. Conspiracy Thinking and Denialism

A core psychological predisposition contributing to hoax beliefs is conspiracy thinking â€” the tendency to view major events as the result of secret plots by powerful groups. This mindset often coexists with denialism, a rejection of expert information and scientific consensus. Research from the Harvard Kennedy School highlights that these psychological traits, combined with partisan and ideological motivations, strongly predict belief in COVID-19 conspiracy theories, including the idea that the virus is a hoax ([Uscinski et al., 2020](https://misinforeview.hks.harvard.edu/article/why-do-people-believe-covid-19-conspiracy-theories/)).

### 2. Need for Cognitive Closure and Pattern Recognition

Humans have an innate desire to make sense of complex and uncertain situations by connecting dots and creating coherent narratives. The pandemic, with its rapid spread and invisible threat, creates anxiety and uncertainty. Conspiracy theories offer simple, often emotionally satisfying explanations that reduce uncertainty and provide a sense of control ([Ries, 2020](https://www.huffpost.com/entry/psychology-why-people-believe-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories_l_5ec46c59c5b6956f4169cea4)).

### 3. Optimism Bias and Unrealistic Risk Assessment

Many individuals engage in unrealistic optimism about their personal risk of contracting COVID-19, leading them to downplay the virus's severity or deny its existence altogether. This bias can result in non-compliance with public health measures and skepticism about official information ([Franco, 2020](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/platonic-love/202003/bias-explains-why-people-dont-take-covid-19-seriously)).

---

## Sociopolitical Factors

### 1. Distrust in Government and Institutions

Distrust in government and official institutions is a significant driver of hoax beliefs. The Oxford survey found that 59% of adults in England believed to some extent that the government was misleading the public about the virus's cause ([Young, 2020](https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-hoax-government-misleading-man-made-survey-a9527876.html)). This distrust is often linked to broader conspiracy mentalities, including skepticism about vaccinations and climate change.

### 2. Partisan and Ideological Influences

Political polarization has played a critical role in shaping COVID-19 perceptions. In the United States, for instance, Republican leaders and right-wing media personalities have downplayed the virus's threat, sometimes labeling it a "hoax" or exaggeration. This rhetoric has influenced their supporters' beliefs and behaviors, leading to higher rates of skepticism and conspiracy theory endorsement among certain political groups ([Uscinski et al., 2020](https://misinforeview.hks.harvard.edu/article/why-do-people-believe-covid-19-conspiracy-theories/)).

### 3. Social Identity and Group Protection

People often adopt conspiracy beliefs to protect their group identity and ideological worldview. Believing in hoaxes can serve as a form of social cohesion within like-minded communities, reinforcing shared narratives and distrust of outsiders ([Ries, 2020](https://www.huffpost.com/entry/psychology-why-people-believe-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories_l_5ec46c59c5b6956f4169cea4)).

---

## Role of Misinformation and Media Environment

### 1. Spread of Misinformation and Disinformation

The COVID-19 "infodemic" has been characterized by an overwhelming amount of misinformation, including false claims about the virus's origin, severity, and treatments. Videos like "Plandemic" and unfounded theories about 5G towers or vaccines have circulated widely on social media, fueling skepticism and hoax beliefs ([Ries, 2020](https://www.huffpost.com/entry/psychology-why-people-believe-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories_l_5ec46c59c5b6956f4169cea4)).

### 2. Media Echo Chambers and Confirmation Bias

Individuals tend to consume media that aligns with their pre-existing beliefs, reinforcing their skepticism and conspiracy thinking. This selective exposure creates echo chambers where misinformation thrives and is rarely challenged ([English, 2022](https://www.acsh.org/news/2022/01/07/covid-denialism-how-much-does-misinformation-explain-16047)).

### 3. Distrust in Scientific Research

Belief that scientific research is politically motivated or biased undermines public trust in health guidance. A study of 12,000 U.S. respondents found that many believe politics drive scientific research, which correlates with lower risk assessments of COVID-19 and resistance to preventative measures ([McLaughlin et al., 2021](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0249937)).

---

## Consequences of Hoax Beliefs

Belief in COVID-19 conspiracy theories and hoaxes is associated with negative health behaviors, including lower compliance with social distancing, mask-wearing, and vaccination. A longitudinal Dutch study found that conspiracy beliefs predicted a higher likelihood of contracting COVID-19, job loss, and poorer well-being over time ([van Prooijen, 2021](https://www.psypost.org/2021/10/belief-in-covid-19-conspiracy-theories-linked-to-a-greater-likelihood-of-contracting-the-virus-study-finds-61998)).

